  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages:\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (US)\n- First international recognition of money laundering as a financial crime\n\n2. Key Milestones:\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- 1990: First EU Money Laundering Directive\n- 2001: USA PATRIOT Act expanded anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n\n3. Regulatory Developments:\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Mandatory suspicious transaction reporting\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n\n4. Recent Trends:\n- Cryptocurrency and digital asset regulations\n- Enhanced corporate transparency laws\n- Expanded beneficial ownership disclosure requirements\n- More sophisticated digital monitoring technologies\n\n5. Global Compliance Frameworks:\n- Risk-based approach to AML\n- Continuous updates to international standards\n- Ongoing sanctions and enforcement mechanisms\n\n6. Technology Integration:\n- Artificial intelligence and machine learning in detecting financial crimes\n- Advanced transaction monitoring systems\n- Enhanced data analytics for identifying suspicious patterns\n\nLegislation continues to adapt to emerging financial technologies and evolving money laundering strategies.",
